    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1888-10-27T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1888-10-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="515"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d515">
                <head>No. 60.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bayard</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Garland</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1888-10-27">
                            <hi rend="italic">October</hi> 27, 1888</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to previous correspondence concerning
                    the disposition of the British vessels <hi rend="italic">Grace, Dolphin</hi>,
                    and <hi rend="italic">Anna Beck</hi>, condemned for taking seals illicitly in
                    Behring Sea, I have the honor to acknowledge the receipt of your letter of the
                    20th instant on the subject, and <pb facs="0859" n="1817" xml:id="pg_1817"/> to
                    say in reply that, under the circumstances, the wiser course for all concerned
                    is to let the sale take place at once, as delay is impracticable and can only be
                    productive of loss.</p>
                <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">T. F. Bayard.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
